Reading the Ray Peat article on carrageenans is funny because it's based around the phenomenon of persorption, which seems to be a basic biological function, but it's so obscure, to the point that googling it will suggest you made a typo, it doesn't even have a Wikipedia article

You can find stuff on it easily still, it's just all old and on random niche journals or whatever, just good to remember 99% of nutritionists, scientists, etc. are not even aware this has ever existed as a basic concept when they talk about more advanced stuff

Like it's not some advanced theoretic bullshit with nanomolecule mumbo jumbo, it's literally just the intestine pulling large starch particles or some other stuff and them getting stuck in smaller blood vessels, observable with simple lab tools, but no one really mentions it ever

The "official" hypothesis is that she was in love with a foreigner with whom she corresponded by letters, then suddenly he stopped responding and disappeared. Also apparently she was blamed for some minor crime (vandalism?) she didn't commit by the communist party

her last diary entries are very harrowing, she talks about finding joy in suffering and wishing she suffered more, then talks about man not being able to reach the divine, then about life being illusionary, filthy, corrupted... but I believe there is more to the story, unspelled

My grandpa used to talk about long-gone winters with snowstorms so severe, that the people had to dig snow-roofed tunnels between the houses to pass resources among each other. The entire village basically turned into an igloo, an ant colony. Cold reduces us to our most naked.

The fact that such intense snowfall no longer seems to occur just shows how dynamic of a thing "climate" is, most people now do not even own a sled, good to remember how easy a settlement used to be (or still is) able to get wiped out in cold famine
